{{Infobox scientist | name = George Joseph | image = GeorgeJoseph.jpg | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1938|08|04|df=y}} | birth_place = Chengannur, [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]] | residence = Ahmedabad, India | nationality = Indian | field = Satellite Imaging Sensors, Remote Sensing and Space Science | work_institution = Space Applications Center, ISRO, Center for Space Science and Technology Education in Asia and the Pacific(affiliated to UN) | known_for = Pioneering contribution to the Indian Space programme in the area of earth observation technology. | prizes = [[Padma Bhushan]] (1999) | website = {{url|http://www.profgeorgej.com}} | religion = | footnotes = }}
'''George Joseph''' (born 4 August 1938) is an Indian space scientist, best known for his contributions to the development of [[remote sensing]] technology in India, especially in the field of earth observation sensors. He is a former chairman of the Lunar Mission Study Task Force of the [[Indian Space Research Organization]] and an elected fellow of the [[National Academy of Sciences, India]], [[Indian Academy of Sciences]] and [[Indian National Academy of Engineering]]. The [[Government of India]] awarded him the [[Padma Bhushan]], the third highest civilian award, in 1999.
==Early life== {{BLP unsourced section|date=April 2018}} George Joseph was born on 4 August 1938 to Advocate M. G. Joseph and Alice in [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]]. After completing schooling, he joined [[St.Berchmans College]], [[Changanassery]] and also attended Alagappa Chettiar College in [[Karaikudi]] and [[University College, Trivandrum]]. He served as lecturer in [[Union Christian College, Aluva]] and at [[CMS College Kottayam]]. Afterwards he was a trainee at [[Bhabha Atomic Research Center]] (BARC), [[Mumbai|Bombay]].
Joseph is married to Mercy and they have two sons.
==Research career==
Joseph started his research career in 1962 at the [[Tata Institute of Fundamental Research]](TIFR), Bombay, where he was involved in the study of cosmic rays.<ref name="Dr George Joseph Awarded India's Civilian Award and Premier Remote Sensing Award">{{Cite web |url=http://www.isprs.org/publications/highlights/highlights0402/indianaward.pdf |title=Dr George Joseph Awarded India's Civilian Award and Premier Remote Sensing Award |date=2018-06-07 |website=ISPRS |access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> Based on his research work at TIFR he was awarded PhD degree by the Bombay University. A novel detector system designed by him was flown on the first Indian satellite [[Aryabhata (satellite)]] to detect solar neutrons.<ref>[http://www.sac.gov.in/asac-leaders-g-joseph.html SAC Directors]</ref>
==Contributions to the Indian Space Programme==
In 1973, Joseph was invited to join the [[Space Applications Centre]], Ahmedabad-one of the centers of the [[Indian Space Research Organization]] (ISRO),and initiated the development of remote sensing technology particularly sensors of various types.<ref name="Space Applications Centre profile">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sac.gov.in/Vyom/Dr.GeorgeJoseph.jsp |title=Space Applications Centre profile |date=2018-06-07 |website=www.sac.gov.in |access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> He has been the guiding force in the design and development of all the earth observation cameras on board [[Indian Remote Sensing Satellite]](IRS) and [[INSAT]]. He served ISRO in various capacities including Director, Space Applications Centre and took keen interest and initiative to ensure the fruits of space technology reach common man. One of the noteworthy contributions of Joseph is the study report on Indian Mission to Moon in the capacity as Chairman, Lunar Mission Study Task Force.<ref>[http://www.wsws.org/articles/2002/sep2002/indi-s06.shtml What lies behind India’s planned trip to the moon?]</ref><ref name="Moon within our reach: Isro - Times of India">{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Moon-within-our-reach-Isro/articleshow/18898116.cms |title=Moon within our reach: Isro - Times of India |date=August 12, 2002 |website=The Times of India |access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref>
Joseph has served in a number of national and international committees/organizations including President of Technical Commission -I of the International Society for Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing ([[ISPRS]])<ref>[http://www.isprs.org/technical_commissions9600/tc_1.html ISPRS Technical Commission -I]</ref> during 1996-2000 and Director, Centre for Space Science and Technology Education in Asia and the Pacific (CSSTEAP), (affiliated to the United Nations), with headquarters at Dehradun during 2006-2009.<ref name="Dr George Joseph Appointed Director of UN-affiliated Centre for Space Science and Technology Education in Asia and the Pacific - ISRO">{{Cite web |url=https://www.isro.gov.in/update/08-dec-2006/dr-george-joseph-appointed-director-of-un-affiliated-centre-space-science-and |title=Dr George Joseph Appointed Director of UN-affiliated Centre for Space Science and Technology Education in Asia and the Pacific - ISRO |website=www.isro.gov.in |language=en |access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref><ref>[http://www.isro.org/pressrelease/scripts/pressreleasein.aspx?Dec08_2006 Dr George Joseph Appointed Director of UN-affiliated Centre for Space Science and Technology Education in Asia and the Pacific]</ref><ref>[http://www.cssteap.org/george.html Center for Space Science & Technology Education in Asia & The Pacific (CSSTEAP)]</ref>
==Fellowship/ Membership of professional bodies== * Fellow [[Indian Academy of Sciences]] (FASc)<ref name="Fellowship - Indian Academy of Sciences">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ias.ac.in/describe/fellow/Joseph,_Prof._George |title=Fellowship - Indian Academy of Sciences |date=2018-06-07 |website=www.ias.ac.in |language=en |access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> * Fellow [[National Academy of Sciences, India]] (FNASc)<ref name="The National Academy of Sciences, India - Fellows">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nasi.org.in/fellows.asp?RsFilter=J |title=The National Academy of Sciences, India - Fellows |date=2018-06-07 |website=www.nasi.org.in |access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> * Fellow [[Indian National Academy of Engineering]] (FNAE) * Fellow Indian Geophysical Union * Fellow Gujarat Science Academy * Fellow Indian Meteorological Society<ref name="Members List – IMS">{{Cite web |url=http://imetsociety.org/members-list/ |title=Members List – IMS |date=2018-06-07 |website=imetsociety.org |access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> * Fellow Indian Society of Remote Sensing (ISRS) * Fellow Astronautical Society of India
